<HEADLINE>
<P>
NO ART TO MURDER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 So Wendy Lesser would have us believe that we view true-life murders as artful 
theater and any given murderer as "the lead actor in a tragedy" ("Homicidal 
Tendencies," Dec. 12). I don't think so.Lesser is glorifying these acts of 
cowardly violence, thrusting the scum who perpetrate them into the limelight 
while the victims become only nameless, faceless statistics. This is not a 
science project we're talking about here; it's coldblooded murder. 
</P>
<P>
 T. A. YATKIN 
</P>
<P>
 El Segundo 
</P>
<P>
 It is almost five years since I lost my companion to a murderer. It's 
revolting to think that someone like Lesser would have been entertained by the 
evening-news footage of the police carrying him away in a body bag. Or that her 
unappeasable curiosity would have led her to devour the unfair and distorted 
newspaper articles devoted to his brutal killing. 
</P>
<P>
 Murder is neither mysterious nor fascinating -- nor something that can be 
admired for its curious craft by any compassionate human being. 
</P>
<P>
 BETH ANN LAHICKEY 
</P>
<P>
 Costa Mesa 
</P>
