177 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAPERBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 OBASAN by Joy Kogawa (Anchor: $9; 300 pp.) and ITSUKA by Joy Kogawa (Anchor: 
$9; 334 pp.). Kogawa's semi-autobiographical novels trace the internment of 
Japanese-Canadians during World War II and their subsequent struggle for 
redress."Obasan" (a respectful term for aunt), introduces the reader to Naomi 
Nakane and her prosperous family. Forced to leave their home in Vancouver, the 
Nakanes are sent to a series of inland camps and abandoned villages. Their only 
crime is their Asian ancestry, "the hair shirt of ethnicity." Left in the care 
of her aged aunt, Naomi witnesses the painful disintegration of the people she 
loves. "Itsuka" ("Someday") traces the gradual return to a semblance of normal 
life after the War. Kogawa shows the reader the frustration of the Nakanes with 
Caucasians who see only skin color and refuse to distinguish soldiers of the 
Imperial Army from fellow-citizens of Japanese descent. In eloquent, 
understated prose, she depicts the long battle for vindication, despite 
internecine quarrels and cultural biases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
