<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 DIE, DOZENS INJURED IN PILEUPS IN FOG; CRASHES: MORE THAN 70 VEHICLES WERE 
INVOLVED IN COLLISIONS IN THE CENTRAL VALLEY. VISIBILITY ALONG SOME STRETCHES 
OF CALIFORNIA 99 WAS LESS THAN 50 FEET. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JESSE KATZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Motorists speeding through the San Joaquin Valley's dense winter fog triggered 
a series of chain-reaction crashes Saturday that left two dead, at least 60 
injured and more than 70 vehicles piled up in Livingston and Selma, authorities 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 All the collisions occurred on California 99, where eight accidents were 
reported within an hour after sunrise. Along some shrouded stretches of 
freeway, visibility was less than 50 feet, and California Highway Patrol 
officers blamed drivers for traveling too fast and following too close. 
</P>
<P>
 "When it's foggy, you have to slow down," said CHP Officer Ron Minor of the 
Fresno division. "I drive in this stuff every day. I do it for a living. But 
some mornings, people pass me like I'm standing still." 
</P>
<P>
 The worst crash was near Selma, a small farming community about 12 miles south 
of Fresno. Heavy fog brought traffic to a screeching halt on the southbound 
lanes of California 99, where 15 vehicles quickly piled up, including a small 
passenger car sandwiched between a 45-foot lumber truck and a 45-foot truck 
carrying spaghetti sauce. 
</P>
<P>
 By afternoon, emergency crews were still working to unload the trucks and tow 
them away in an effort to get to the smashed car, which contained the two 
victims who died, police said. The bodies were not immediately identified. 
</P>
<P>
 Also caught in the wreckage was a tour bus filled with more than 50 Korean 
students headed to Disneyland, according to authorities. Six youths were taken 
to hospitals, but officers did not believe that any were seriously injured. 
</P>
<P>
 "There were about 12 cars piled up and I would have run into them if I hadn't 
been flagged down," Perry Rath, a 35-year-old motorist from Fresno, told 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
 About half a mile south of there, officers were trying to separate 32 vehicles 
that had piled up along the highway. Together, the two crashes injured 49 
people, including one victim who remained in critical condition Saturday at 
Valley Medical Center in Fresno. 
</P>
<P>
 At the same time, near the Merced County town of Livingston, authorities were 
investigating six collisions involving 29 vehicles that occurred in rapid 
succession along a foggy one-mile stretch of California 99. Police said 12 
people were treated for mostly minor injuries, although one man remained in 
critical condition at Memorial North Hospital in Modesto after he apparently 
climbed out of his pickup and was struck by a larger truck. 
</P>
<P>
 "There was one wreck, then pretty soon another, then another, and so forth," 
said CHP Sgt. Jim Balestra. Pileup on California 99 
</P>
<P>
 The San Joaquin Valley's dense winter fog was blamed for a series of 
chain-reaction collisions that left more than 70 vehicles piled up on 
California 99 Saturday, killing at least two people and injuring five dozen. 
The worst crash was a 15-car tangle on the outskirts of Selma. About half a 
mile south, 32 vehicles slammed into each other. A series of six smaller 
crashes, involving 29 vehicles, occurred about 90 miles to the north, near 
Livingston. 
</P>
</TEXT>
